(53, 'P. Clay Sherrod', 'ASO - Conway', '22P - Kopff', '2002-06-15 07:00:00', '14.63', '', '9"', '03/09/16', 'n/a', '0.31m SCT with SBIG STV at f/3.75, 30 sec. exposures', 'Very tiny but nebulous; sky conditions perfect; comet confirmed via blink motion, 3 images, 40 minutes. Beautiful sky conditions.~', ''),
(54, 'P. Clay Sherrod', 'ASO - Conway', '24P Schaumasse', '2002-06-02 07:00:00', '15.19', '', '4"', '05/09/16', '225', '0.31m SCT with SBIG STV at f/3.75, 25 sec. exposures', 'Short tail or extension detected for 8" at PA 225; comet is round, diffuse and difficult in moonlight.~', ''),
(55, 'P. Clay Sherrod', 'ASO - Conway', '29P Schwassmann-Wachmann', '2002-06-15 07:00:00', '12.61', '', '1.2''', '06/09/16', 'none', '0.31m SCT with SBIG STV at f/3.75, 30 sec. exposures', 'Incredible view of this outburst; comet coma is distinctly "DUMBBELL" shaped (see image) with central core measured CCD at m2 = 15.31. Perimeter of comet is very irregular. The comet is very large and bright, easy to spot in a 6" telescope.', 'schwas_0615.JPG'),
(56, 'P. Clay Sherrod', 'ASO - Conway', '29P Schwassmann-Wachmann', '2002-06-17 07:00:00', '13.11', '', '1.5''', '06/09/16', '235 ?', '0.31m SCT with SBIG STV at f/3.75, 30 sec. exposures', 'An incredible view of the comet''s coma, showing what appears to be a spiral outgassing in the attached image. Comet is larger than on 6-15-02, although somewhat fainter. Note the interesting spiral pattern (rotational attributes?) along the periphery of the comet and the dark "gap" at 235 degrees, this also noted on the previous observation.', 'Schwas_0617.jpg'),
(57, 'P. Clay Sherrod', 'ASO - Conway', '29P Schwassmann-Wachmann', '2002-06-18 07:00:00', '13.09', '', '2.1''', '07/09/16', '230 ?', '0.31m SCT with SBIG STV at f/3.75, 30 sec. exposures', 'Still and incredible display of this comet in outburst. The comet - Although not inordinately bright - is quite large and this morning is showing a clear nucleus measured via CCD at m2 = 14.62. The coma continues to demonstrate the "curving pinwheel" effect as recorded on June 17 as clearly seen in the accompanying image. The inset in this image was imaged at f/5 for 50 seconds via CCD and clearly shows the nearly stellar nuclear condensation.', 'SchwasW_0618.jpg'),
(58, 'P. Clay Sherrod', 'ASO - Conway', '29P Schwassmann-Wachmann', '2002-06-18 07:00:00', '', '', '', '', '', '0.31m SCT with SBIG STV at f/3.75, 30 sec. exposures', 'COMPUTER ENHANCED IMAGE OF ASO IMAGE. Brian Sherrod used an edge enhancement technique to define the curving spiral nature of this remarkable coma.', 'SW_edge_detect.jpg'),
(59, 'P. Clay Sherrod', 'ASO - Conway', '29P Schwassmann-Wachmann', '2002-06-19 07:00:00', '13.06', '', '1.1', '06/09/16', 'n/a', '0.31m SCT with SBIG STV at f/3.75, 30 sec. exposures', 'Irregular perimeter still notable; the dark gap at near PA 230 deg. is still evident, but not nearly as prominent as on previous night; no tail; comet seems quite steady in brightness. Detailed images still reveal spiral nature of coma.~', ''),
(60, 'P. Clay Sherrod', 'ASO - Conway', '29P Schwassmann-Wachmann', '2002-06-20 07:00:00', '13.22', '', '2.1''', '07/09/16', 'none', '0.31m SCT with SBIG STV at f/3.75, 30 sec. exposures', 'An incredible show continues with the spiralling nature of the coma and nucleus clearly evident in the attached negative image via CCD (3-40sec. composite). Nucleus (m2) magnitude measured at 14.09; no tail; note the conspicuous curing "arms" of the comet in this image.', 'SchwaW_0620.jpg'),
(61, 'Brian', 'ASO', '29P Schwassmann-Wachmann', '2002-06-20 07:00:00', '', '', '', '', '', 'Same as previous record this date.', 'Computer modified image by Brian Sherrod showing what could be two particles orbiting the nucleus of this comet.', 'swmod.jpg'),
(62, 'P. Clay Sherrod', 'ASO - Conway', '29P Schwassmann-Wachmann', '2002-06-21 07:00:00', '13.1', '', '2.5''', '2/9*', 'none', '0.31m SCT with SBIG STV at f/3.75, 30 sec. exposures', '* the comet is very wide and diffuse uniformly across its coma...however, the central core (m2) magnitude is measured at 14.77, clearly concentrated. Note the incredible spiral nature via the attached image.', '29P_0621_380.JPG'),
(63, 'P. Clay Sherrod', 'ASO - Conway', '29P Schwassmann-Wachmann', '2002-06-21 07:00:00', '13.1', '', 'n/a', '', '', '0.31m SCT with SBIG STV at f/3.75, 30 sec. exposures', 'COMPOSITE SHOWING MORPHOLOGY CHANGES IN 29P Schwassmann-Wachmann in 0.5 hour on June 21.380 to 21.388.', 'ScwasW_0621comp.jpg'),
(64, 'P. Clay Sherrod', 'ASO - Conway', '29P Schwassmann-Wachmann', '2002-07-04 07:00:00', '*m2 = 14.35', '', 'n/a', 'm2 = 7/9', 'none', '0.31m SCT with SBIG STV at f/3.75, 90 sec. exposure 1x gain, 320 x 200 pixels @ 14.8 microns', 'm2 (nuclear) measurements only - * nucleus/central coma measurements only; heavy haze prevented detection of extent of coma; coma was incredibly transparent and vague; no tail~', ''),
(65, 'P. Clay Sherrod', 'ASO - Conway', '29P Schwassmann-Wachmann', '2002-07-06 07:00:00', '*m2 = 14.90', '', '12"', '07/09/16', 'n/a', '0.31m SCT with SBIG STV at f/3.75, 90 sec. exposure 1x gain, 320 x 200 pixels @ 14.8 microns', 'Very faint, but fairly large and uniformly diffuse and round; *conditions preclude accurate m1 measurement; much ground fog, heavy haze ~', ''),
(66, 'P. Clay Sherrod', 'ASO - Conway', '29P Schwassmann-Wachmann', '2002-07-07 07:00:00', '14.89', '', '12-15" *', '05/09/16', 'n/a', '0.31m SCT with SBIG STV at f/3.75, 90 sec. exposure 1x gain, 320 x 200 pixels @ 14.8 microns', 'Comet is considerably irregular, [*]with three areas of equal brightening within a very irregular and patchy coma; considerably fainter now; imaging and estimates difficult do to proximity to 14th magn. star.~', ''),
(67, 'P. Clay Sherrod', 'ASO - Conway', '29P Schwassmann-Wachmann', '2002-07-08 07:00:00', 'm2 = 14.89', '', '0.8''', '06/09/16', '162', '0.31m SCT with SBIG STV at f/3.75, 90 sec. exposure 1x gain, 320 x 200 pixels @ 14.8 microns', 'Comet coma is very difficult to discern in larger scope; distinct nuclear condensation of 14.89 recorded; faint extension at PA 162 deg for 1.1'' length~', ''),
(68, 'P. Clay Sherrod', 'ASO - Conway', '29P Schwassmann-Wachmann', '2002-07-09 07:00:00', '*m2 = 14.87', '', '1.4''', '02/09/16', 'n/a', '0.31m SCT with SBIG STV at f/3.75, 90 sec. exposure 1x gain, 320 x 200 pixels @ 14.8 microns', 'Comet coma is very difficult to discern in larger scope, hence no m1 total mag. given; nuclear condensation not seen as strongly tonight, likely because of deteriorating conditions~', ''),
