(73, 'P. Clay Sherrod', 'ASO - Conway', '29P Schwassmann-Wachmann', '2002-08-06 07:00:00', '11.1 (*m2 = 13.29)', '', '0.6 oval', '08/09/16', '200 (?)', '0.31m SCT @ f/3.75; SBIG/STV ccd @ 320 x 300 pixels, 14.8/pixel (gain = 1 to reduce SN ratio). 90 second exposures, unprocessed. Photometry via computer direct (ccdSoft).', 'Still an extraordinary site, with a highly concentrated coma and distinct offset (toward NNE) nuclear center; this can possibly indicate a tail in PA 200 deg; coma is oval shaped and uniformly bright with several indications, particularly on the W. side, of irregularities; note that m1 estimate is visual via 0.31m SCT while 13.29 (*)m2 is ccd]', '29P_0806.jpg'),
(74, 'P. Clay Sherrod', 'ASO - Conway', '29P Schwassmann-Wachmann', '2002-08-12 07:00:00', '11.94 (*m2=14.03)', '', '1.8', '08/09/16', '182-205', 'image/photometry via 0.31m SCT @ f/3.75; SBIG/STV ccd @ 320 x 300 pixels, 14.8/pixel (gain = 1 to reduce SN ratio). 90 second exposures, unprocessed. Photometry via computer direct (ccdSoft).', 'A fanned tail, 182 to 205deg, about 1.1 length is now noted on this spectacular comet; very intense coma with clearly distinct nucleus (*m2=14.03; considerable irregular detail, perhaps outgassing jets, are seen on W perimeter of comet; NOTE: arrow on image indicates diffuse object imaged on seven-set sequence demonstrating SAME motion as 29P; object is not stellar', '29P_0807.jpg'),
